\par\par \b \uc2  Experts say LoI targets reprieve for businesses. \b0\par\par\uc2 700 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 August 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  12 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Businesses can expect a recovery in investment activities following the signing of The International Monetary Fund's (IMF) Letter of Intent (LoI), experts said on Tuesday. \par \par \uc2  Bustanul Arifin of the Institute for Development of Economics and Finance (Indef) said he expected a jump in investments on the back of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform targets under the LoI. \par \par \uc2  "In the long run we'll see more investment flowing in," Bustanul told The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2  He said several points in the recently signed LoI opened the door for revitalizing the country's dull investment growth. \par \par \uc2  He said the IMF, in relaxing its base money supply target to Rp 110.5 trillion (about US$12.31 billion) from Rp 108 trillion, eased pressure on \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been raising \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  to absorb the money supply, curbing pressure on inflation and the rupiah. \par \par \uc2  With a current base money supply at over Rp 111 trillion, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been reluctant to cut \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Instead, rates have been steadily rising even after the rupiah has firmed. From 14 percent early this year, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's three month promissory notes could test 18 percent this week. \par \par \uc2  Given the high rates, it has become difficult for banks to expand their lending portfolio to businesses. \par \par \uc2  Lowering the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  is essential to allow banks to reduce theirs and thus lower the cost of borrowing for businesses. \par \par \uc2  "We hope that banks will soon resume its intermediary role in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Bustanul explained. \par \par \uc2  Without the banking sector pushing investment, analysts remain gloomy over Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth outlook. \par \par \uc2  The government has said its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  priority is the creation of more jobs, which is a prerequisite for higher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. \par \par \uc2  Economist Hadi Soesastro has estimated Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  must grow by 7 percent to absorb a 2.5 percent growth of the country's work force. \par \par \uc2  Under the LoI, the government expects the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , as measured by its Gross Domestic Product (GDP), to grow between 3 percent and 3.5 percent. \par \par \uc2  "For every increase of 1 percent in GDP, the government provides 400,000 new jobs," Bustanul continued. \par \par \uc2  Another boost for the real sector is the LoI's demand for contingency funds worth Rp 3 trillion to help \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  provinces, he added. \par \par \uc2  The funds are part of the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  decentralization \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to help the budgets of poorer regions. \par \par \uc2  "The funds will go to regional administrations for \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , meaning that it will be spent on local economies," Bustanul said. \par \par \uc2  He said that as the IMF largely dealt with monetary policies, most of the LoI's impact on businesses would only be felt in the long term. \par \par \uc2  He cited as an example structural reforms, such as promoting good corporate governance and legal certainty, which would take time to bear fruit. \par \par \uc2  Turning to the informal sector of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Bustanul said, the impact of the LoI there would be even less significant. \par \par \uc2  "It's not the IMF's job to deal with our informal \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and the government also focuses more on the formal \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he said. \par \par \uc2  Nonetheless, he said, the IMF and the government acknowledged the importance of the informal sector, which had absorbed much of the country's work force when the manufacturing sector, as well as other sectors, went bust during the 1997 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  Bustanul said the informal sector would benefit from the impact of which a healthier state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  would have on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  National \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Recovery Committee (KPEN) executive Anton J. Supit described the LoI as start-up capital for the government to lead the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  into recovery. \par \par \uc2  He said the signing of the LoI encouraged foreign investors to take interest again in Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  But Anton warned that most of the problems that had blocked their entrance were related to issues outside the LoI. \par \par \uc2  "Now that the door has opened to new investment, it will be up to the government to do its homework on cleaning up old problems," he said. \par \par \uc2  He cited rampant security threats, inconsistency in government policies and legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the real menace behind the disappearance of foreign investors.(bkm) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document j