\par\par \b \uc2  2002 growth target within reach - Economists. \b0\par\par\uc2 721 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 September 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Noted economists expressed optimism that given the current relatively stable political condition, the 2002 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth target of "less than five percent", as recently indicated by Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Dorodjatun Kuntjoro-Jakti, would be attainable. \par \par \uc2  Economists contacted by the Jakarta Post on Saturday, including Pande Raja Silalahi of the Centre for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS), Raden Pardede of Danareksa Institute, Anton Gunawan of Citibank, and Bustanul Arifin of the Institute for Development of Economics and Finance (INDEF) said that Indonesia would easily register an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of between 4.5 percent and 4.75 percent next year. \par \par \uc2  But they also warned that remaining security problems and legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  faced by businesses, as well as the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recession facing major trading partners, might eclipse Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  "If we can maintain the current political stability, an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of more than four percent is easily attainable," Pande told the Post. \par \par \uc2  "Political stability is a prerequisite for capital inflow, which is expected to help spur \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2002," Raden added. \par \par \uc2  Dorodjatun told reporters on Thursday that Indonesia would record an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of "less than five percent" in 2002, compared with this year's target of 3.5 percent. \par \par \uc2  The relatively high \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth target would be needed if Dorodjatun wants to realize his priority goal of creating employment. \par \par \uc2  Raden said that consumer confidence had improved significantly since President Megawati Soekarnoputri took over the leadership on July 23, but it was not yet sufficient to turn the confidence into \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "Our survey shows that sentiment is improving very rapidly, but it still takes time to change the sentiment to \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he said. \par \par \uc2  According to Raden, strong capital inflow was also expected to stir \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth next year. \par \par \uc2  "At present, investment accounts for 16 percent of gross domestic product. If capital inflow increases just by two percent next year, we will register an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of at least 4.5 percent," he said, adding that the first phase of capital inflow was expected to come from local exporters that deposited their money overseas during the country's twin \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political crises. \par \par \uc2  Asked about the prospects for foreign capital to enter the country, Anton said that overseas investors would maintain their wait-and-see attitude until they witnessed local firms starting to expand. \par \par \uc2  "Foreign capitalists will first observe if domestic firms are already operating at their full capacity before they start pouring in funds," Anton said. \par \par \uc2  He urged the government to expedite the bank restructuring program to allow the industry to resume lending to cash-strapped local companies. \par \par \uc2  "IBRA (the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency) must move fast in restructuring the debts of national banks so that they can become healthy and start lending to national firms," said Anton. \par \par \uc2  "Some sectors, like manufacturing and pharmacy, have long wanted to increase their running capacity and even expand their operations, but could not do it because of financing difficulties," he said. \par \par \uc2  He also said that the government had to encourage firms to find non-bank financing sources, such as by issuing bonds. \par \par \uc2  But he said that national firms had been discouraged in issuing bonds because of the relatively high transaction fee of 0.03 percent. \par \par \uc2  "The government should scrap the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  because it discourages cash-trapped firms from issuing bonds," he said. \par \par \uc2  Anton warned that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth would be overshadowed by \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recession facing the country's major trading partners such as Singapore, Japan, U.S. and some European countries. \par \par \uc2  "Purchasing power in those countries has declined," he said. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, Bustanul called on the government to provide incentives, including \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  facilities, for local firms to resume operations or expand. \par \par \uc2  "The government should waive value-added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  imposed on imported raw materials that are used for exported goods," he said. \par \par \uc2  Asked about the Dorodjatun's plans to boost the country's credit rating from non-investment to investment grade within a six-month period, Raden said that it would be rather difficult, given the complexity of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems. \par \par \uc2  "Taking into account the real condition, it is extremely difficult to improve the credit rating from "ccc+" to "bbb+" within three to six months," he said, adding that a more reasonable timetable would be one year. (03) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Pos