\par\par \b \uc2  U.S. attacks may derail RI's recovery. \b0\par\par\uc2 632 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 September 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Economists warned that terrorist attacks on the U.S. could create a deeper global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recession and derail Indonesia's fledgling \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  "The terrorist attack on New York's World Trade Center towers and Washington's Pentagon could drag the United States into a longer and deeper \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis which could degenerate into a global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recession," economist Sri Adiningsih of the Yogyakarta-based Gadjah Mada University told The Jakarta Post on Saturday. \par \par \uc2  She explained that the impact on Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  could include a drop in exports and foreign investment. \par \par \uc2  "This is worrisome since both the 2001 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the 2002 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  draft cannot stimulate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth," she said. \par \par \uc2  The government has targeted \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of around 5 percent in 2002 compared to the 3.5 percent growth targeted for this year. \par \par \uc2  Two hijacked airplanes slammed into the WTC, and another into the Pentagon last week, creating new \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  There has also been speculation that the attacks will cause the government's macroeconomic assumptions as set out in the 2002 draft \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  to be revised. In addition to the above \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth target, the assumptions include an inflation rate of 8 percent, exchange rate of Rp 8,500 per U.S. dollar, and an international oil price of US$22 per barrel. \par \par \uc2  Local exporter associations had earlier predicted that the terrorist attacks on the U.S. could cause exports to drop by between 10 percent and 20 percent this year. \par \par \uc2  Economist Sjahrir said the terrorist attacks would prompt the U.S., Indonesia's second biggest trading partner and one of the country's large foreign investors, to focus on its own \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and security rather than on international \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues. \par \par \uc2  "The U.S. will likely shift from its current multilateral foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to a unilateral \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Sjahrir said. \par \par \uc2  The government's plan to push the private sector to play a greater role in bringing about a recovery in the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  through accelerating the privatization program and the sale of assets under the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA), could also be undermined as investors would likely adopt a wait-and-see approach for quite sometime. \par \par \uc2  "What we are afraid of is international investors will think that since doing business and investing in the U.S. is no longer safe, doing business and investing in other countries, including Indonesia, is also not safe," Sri said. \par \par \uc2  "If that happens, they will adopt a wait-and-see attitude, which means that the flow of international investment and trade will be sluggish," she added. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, economist Hadi Soesastro of the Centre for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) and Didik J. Rachbini of the Institute for Development of Economics and Finance (Indef), played down the real impact of the terrorist attacks on Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , arguing that the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  difficulties stemmed from domestic problem. \par \par \uc2  "The impact (of the terrorist attacks) is insignificant and indirect," said Hadi. \par \par \uc2  He admitted, however, that the attacks might affect the country's exports to U.S., but argued that any fall would have little bearing on Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. \par \par \uc2  "Export-driven \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is not sustainable since it does not reflect good and sound \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions," said Hadi, adding that increased exports do not necessarily mean sound \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions. \par \par \uc2  He said the priority for Indonesia was to implement the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform agenda pledged to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) if it wanted to put its \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  back on track. \par \par \uc2  Didik concurred with Hadi, saying Indonesia was too far from the U.S. to suffer the impact of the terrorist attacks. \par \par \uc2  He said the attacks could, in fact, serve as a blessing in disguise for Indonesia. (03) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010917dx9h000bn\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
