\par\par \b \uc2  Rupiah, stock market brace for U.S revenge. \b0\par\par\uc2 566 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 September 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Concerns over a U.S. attack against Afghanistan could ignite rupiah, stock selling this week as edgy investors brace for a fully fledged global recession, analysts warned. \par \par \uc2  Currency and stock analyst Feri Latuhihin at PT Danareksa Securities said a U.S. attack that stirs up regional \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , would upset the market here. \par \par \uc2  "It (the attack) could come like a shockwave slashing the market," Feri said over the weekend. \par \par \uc2  The United States is almost certain to attack Afghanistan's ruling Taliban regime over their refusal to hand over Osama Bin Laden. \par \par \uc2  Bin Laden is the prime suspect behind the recent terrorist attacks in New York and Washington. \par \par \uc2  Thousands are feared to have died when two planes crashed into the twin towers of the World Trade Center (WTC) in New York. \par \par \uc2  Mass layoffs in the airline industry mark the aftermath of the attack. Now, fear of more layoffs in other sectors is eroding consumer confidence in the U.S, analysts said. \par \par \uc2  "You would slash your shopping \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , if you were not sure whether you would still have your job tomorrow," said one analyst. \par \par \uc2  Yet a drop in consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  would ultimately cut off the string that kept the U.S \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  from derailing into recession, he said. \par \par \uc2  At this point, Feri said, U.S. retaliation would further the descent into global recession, due to increasing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Analysts warned of an uprising of radicals in more moderate Islamic countries such as Indonesia, should the U.S. invade Afghanistan. \par \par \uc2  "The world is already tilting toward recession, the recent terrorist attacks has just expedited the process," Feri said. \par \par \uc2  At home, he continued, the rupiah could edge to Rp 10,000 to the dollar, once news of the U.S attack hit the market. \par \par \uc2  But according to him, the drop would only be temporary. In the mid-to-long-term the local unit would hover at between Rp 9,000 and Rp 9,500, he said. \par \par \uc2  "\b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  would defend the rupiah if it drops to below 9,500," he predicted, adding that profit-taking on the stronger dollar would also favor the local unit. \par \par \uc2  Traders believe the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  had backed up the rupiah against the greenback during Friday trading. But the rupiah closed the week still lower at 9,410 compared to 9,100 a week earlier. \par \par \uc2  Feri said a weaker dollar in the global market, reflecting the U.S.'s ailing \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , would also lend reprieve to the rupiah. \par \par \uc2  PT Nomura Indonesia stock analyst, Goei Siauw Hong said a U.S attack against Afghanistan was sure to hurt market sentiment. \par \par \uc2  He said, although a war in Afghanistan had little or no direct \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  impact on Indonesia, there was concern the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  might spill over to other regions, notably the Middle East. \par \par \uc2  This gloomy outlook could translate into more than a 4 to 5 percent loss in the market index this week, he predicted. \par \par \uc2  Last Friday, the Jakarta Stock Exchange (JSX) Composite Index slid to 414.42 compared to 425.26 a week before. Dealers said that a decline in the regional market had led to a selling mood. \par \par \uc2  Hong suggested investors steer away from export-oriented companies and focus on those with a healthy domestic market. \par \par \uc2  "Food-producing companies, pharmaceuticals and cigarette companies are always needed, in good times or bad," he said.(bkm) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924dx9o000bn\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
