\par\par \b \uc2  Address investor confidence amid  \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty \highlight\uc2 , slowdown. \b0\par\par\uc2 820 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 September 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  5 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Indonesia, still mired in an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, is among the countries now facing the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  impact of the Sept. 11 attacks in the United States. Mari Pangestu of the Jakarta-based Centre for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) was interviewed by The Jakarta Post contributor A'an Suryana to share her views while she was in Canberra attending an academic conference on women's issues. \par \par \uc2  Question: Amid preparations for the war against terrorists, what is the impact of the U.S. policies and actions on the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ? \par \par \uc2  Answer: The Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is integrated with the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which is now facing grim prospects after the massive terrorist attacks in the U.S., the largest \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  powerhouse. \par \par \uc2  Confidence in the stock market, especially in the U.S., is diminishing after both the attack and President George W. Bush's plan to wage a war against terrorism. The crisis has caused nervousness among investors, discouraging them from buying firms' assets or shares in the stock markets. \par \par \uc2  Once investors are nervous, they choose safer modes of liquid investment, such as deposit or cash accounts, even though investing in the stock market promises higher returns. \par \par \uc2  Having identified this trend, analysts have predicted that the U.S. will suffer a recession next year. \par \par \uc2  The investment downturn in the U.S. will have a harmful effect on our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  because Indonesian exports to the U.S. will eventually decrease. In fact, some Indonesian exporters have complained of canceled orders from their American buyers. Garments, textiles, pulp and paper, and electronics are major Indonesian exports which could be badly affected by the recession. \par \par \uc2  The manufacturing sector could also be hit since this sector is highly integrated with the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The only positive effect we might experience is from the oil and gas sector, which usually enjoys high prices any time supplies from the Middle East are disrupted by war. \par \par \uc2  Amid this global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  downturn, Indonesia may not be able to achieve its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  target of 5 percent growth next year. In the event of a war, would Indonesia see a bank panic similar to the May 1998 riots? \par \par \uc2  There was chaos in the past, but I don't think there will be massive bank runs. Bank depositors have a blanket guarantee from the government. \par \par \uc2  What should the government do to contain the impact? \par \par \uc2  The government can do nothing as the crisis is happening out there, beyond the government's ability to deal with. What the government must do is stimulate domestic demand. (To do this) the government must first restore and maintain investor confidence in the Indonesian market and the consumer market. \par \par \uc2  The government must be able to convince investors that Indonesia is attractive for investment. Today, at least two immediate problems must be solved by the government concerning investment - first, \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  which is caused by lack of physical security and, second, decentralization. \par \par \uc2  Physical security is no longer a major cause for concern today, as compared to the period under Abdurrahman Wahid's government when many large demonstrations took place. However, possible massive riots are again drawing concern after the terrorist attack in the U.S.. \par \par \uc2  Demonstrations against the U.S. are rampant again, and even the U.S. Embassy has sought protection from the police force, avoiding the worst possible case scenario. \par \par \uc2  Terrorist acts have again hit Jakarta (on Sunday explosions occurred at the Atrium Plaza shopping mall in Central Jakarta for the third time since 1998 - Eds.). \par \par \uc2  The government should assure investors that it is able to deal with (terrorist acts), arrest and prosecute the perpetrators, and ensure the safety of their investments. \par \par \uc2  Many American companies today are getting very scared that they may become terrorist targets. \par \par \uc2  The second problem is that \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  still grips the decentralization process. A study carried out by the (Jakarta-based) research organization Smeru in 13 provinces says that regional governments have imposed various \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  or levies, which are detrimental to the business climate. \par \par \uc2  Investors have complained of inadequate enforcement of regulations and lack of coordination between central, provincial and regional administrations. The division of labor in the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  administration is not clear yet and it has caused confusion among investors. \par \par \uc2  For example, investors are still confused about the administration of land titles. The law on regional autonomy stipulates that land title administration must be given to the regional governments, but the Abdurrahman Wahid administration stipulated a presidential decree empowering the central government to handle land titles. This contradictory rule obviously confuses investors interested in building plants or opening plantations. \par \par \uc2  Given the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Indonesia should not rely too heavily on foreign investors and should instead woo domestic investors by encouraging Indonesians, including those who still prefer to park their financial assets overseas. These businesspeople are more willing than foreign investors to take the risk as they know how things run in the country. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010926dx9q0000d\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
