\par\par \b \uc2  U.S. companies in Indonesia remain clam despite threats. \b0\par\par\uc2 702 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 September 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Major U.S. companies operating in Indonesia are remaining calm despite the growing threats made against Americans in the country. \par \par \uc2  Two oil and gas companies, ExxonMobil Oil Indonesia Inc., and PT Caltex Pacific Indonesia, and mining company PT Freeport Indonesia, said that they would continue to monitor the security situation seriously, but they had not yet considered evacuating their employees. \par \par \uc2  "We (will) continue to monitor security conditions in Indonesia and throughout our region, and we will take such steps for the protection of ExxonMobil employees, contractors and property as may be appropriate to the situation," Julia Tumengkol told the Jakarta Post.. \par \par \uc2  She added that ExxonMobil employees and its contractors were of paramount importance to company management. \par \par \uc2  "We have no plans at this time to require expatriate employees or their families to relocate out of Indonesia, " she said. \par \par \uc2  However, the company was organizing a voluntary program for dependents who wished to temporarily return to their home countries, Julia said. \par \par \uc2  ExxonMobil Oil Indonesia Inc., a subsidiary of American giant ExxonMobil Oil Inc., is one of the largest gas producers in the country, with its operations mainly centered in the restive province of Aceh. \par \par \uc2  ExxonMobil has about 50 foreigners among its 1,300 employees. \par \par \uc2  Threats against Americans and U.S. assets in countries with large Muslim populations, including Indonesia, have been increasing following the U.S. government's ultimatum that it would attack Afghanistan for its refusal to hand over Osama bin Laden, who has been accused by the U.S. government of masterminding Sept. 11's devastating attacks on New York and Washington. \par \par \uc2  U.S Ambassador to Indonesia Robert S. Gelbard issued on Thursday for the second time a travel notice for all American citizens in the country to consider their personal security arrangements and, if necessary, consider leaving the country. \par \par \uc2  Separately, Caltex spokesman Renville Almatsier said that the company continued to maintain its heightened security measures, which had been boosted after the U.S. attacks. \par \par \uc2  "However, all of our staff are working normally, including our foreign employees. None of them are taking holidays or being evacuated because of the rising tension," he told the Post. \par \par \uc2  Last week, Renville said Caltex had urged foreign workers to stay in the operation areas for their own safety unless it was necessary to go out. \par \par \uc2  He also said Caltex had intensified identity card examinations at every entrance gate of its strategic business units in Riau. \par \par \uc2  Caltex has also asked the police and military to contribute additional personnel to guard its oil fields, Renville said. \par \par \uc2  Caltex, whose operations are concentrated in Riau, accounts for more than half of the country's 1.3 million barrel per day oil output. The company has a workforce totaling 5,200, including 120 foreigners, most of whom are Americans. \par \par \uc2  Siddharta Moersjid, a spokesman for PT Freeport Indonesia, a subsidiary of New Orleans-based Freeport-McMoran Copper & Gold Inc., also said that his company, so far, had only asked its employees to increase their awareness about the latest situation. \par \par \uc2  "It's still normal, and we haven't given written guidelines yet to our employees," he told the Post. \par \par \uc2  Freeport, the largest gold and copper mining firm in the country, operates its mine in Irian Jaya province. It has about 90 foreign employees out of a total of 9,000 workers. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, Major General Mahidin Simbulon, Chief of the Trikora Military Regional Command in Jayapura, the capital city of Irian Jaya, was downbeat about the growing threats against Americans throughout the country, saying he doubted anything would happen in the province. \par \par \uc2  However, he pledged to safeguard the facilities of Freeport from any threats, saying any disruption to the company would also affect the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  He added that the military had dispatched a special unit to protect the facilities. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, Gelbard was quoted by chairman of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 ' Commission I for security affairs, Ibrahim Ambong, as saying that at least eight American companies had threatened to relocate overseas if the situation continued to be \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Ambong was speaking to the press following a consultation meeting between the House and Gelbard on Friday.(iwa/rms/35) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011001dx9t000hf\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  IMF wants RI to fulfill commitment to privatization. \b0\par\par\uc2 310 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 October 2001\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The IMF representative in Jakarta David Nellor hopes to see the government committed to privatizing state firms (BUMNs) and selling assets of IBRA. \par \par \uc2  In the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  APBN 2001, the government set a target of privatizing BUMNs worth Rp6.5 trillion and sale of assets worth Rp27 trillion. \par \par \uc2  "The effort will face many challenges," said Nellor after speaking at the National Privatization Conference in Jakarta yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Many investors, he added, are trying to avoid risks due to the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slump. \par \par \uc2  Investors, he said further, refrain from investing in emerging markets and as such Indonesia will have problems drawing foreign investors to buy BUMNs or IBRA assets. \par \par \uc2  "But this does not mean the government should revise the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 ." \par \par \uc2  State Minister of State Firms Laksamana Sukardi also asserted that the government would not make any move to revise the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 's targets. \par \par \uc2  He added that although the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  faces recession, Indonesia needs no to revise the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  He also noted that obstacles stand in the way of privatization and sale of IBRA assets worth Rp33.5 trillion, pointing at domestic politics, legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and xenophobia, especially that which are related to divestment of state assets. \par \par \uc2  On the other hand is the bad global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation, he added. \par \par \uc2  However, he is confident that the targets would be reached if there were legal reforms that would have a positive impact on doing business in Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  He further said that privatization is not a matter of selling state assets only but also legal enforcement. \par \par \uc2  On debt rescheduling in APBN 2002, Nellor said the subject is too premature to be discussed as it will be taken up by Indonesia with donor countries. \par \par \uc2  He added, however, that donor countries have pledged to the government in getting loans as an alternative financing mode in RAPBN 2002. (m04). \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020011003dxa30005m\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
