\par\par \b \uc2  Intrusive legislature. \b0\par\par\uc2 702 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 October 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Megawati Soekarnoputri's rise to the presidency in July with strong coalition support created a market belief that her government would be able to speed up its long-delayed reform agenda through the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  But what the government has been facing so far is an overzealous \b \highlight22\uc2 House\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  which attempts to intervene into virtually every program the government is pursuing. This meddling by the legislature has been so excessive that many \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures are stuck in delay after delay at the expense of the government's credibility domestically and internationally. \par \par \uc2  Having said all that, we are not suggesting that the House be as submissive as its predecessors during the authoritarian Soeharto administration, rubber stamping any proposals from the executive branch. But what we see now is a House that has swung from an extremely subservient posture to an overly intrusive one. \par \par \uc2  Since many reform programs have fallen far behind schedule, either because of backtracking by the previous administrations or obstructive meddling by the House, the government often feels compelled to "buy its way" through the legislature to expedite things. Hence, allegations have been abound about how particular ministers made payments, which were disguised in seemingly legal expense accounts, to House members. Recently, a major controversy erupted after Rp 10 million worth of traveler's checks owned by Treasury Director General Anshari Ritonga was found by a cleaner on the eighth floor of the House building. \par \par \uc2  The House should certainly exercise effective control of the government to ensure good governance that is both transparent and accountable but this responsibility must be done appropriately within the parameters of the law and the Constitution. \par \par \uc2  The People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), the country's top \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  body, has set a five-year plan of broad guidelines on state policies to direct government operations, and the policies must be implemented through the annual state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  which must be approved by the House. Hence, House deliberations on the annual state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  plan are supposed to be the most efficient and effective way of controlling governmental operations. \par \par \uc2  But once the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  plan and its programs are approved, the House should no longer intervene into every deal or move the government is making as long as the measures are consistent with the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  programs, other regulations and budgetary procedures. \par \par \uc2  The most glaring examples are debt restructuring, asset sales and privatization of state companies, which are core elements of reforms and vital to stop the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  bleeding. \par \par \uc2  The 2001 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which was approved by the House late last year, clearly details the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  objectives and revenue targets of those reform measures and also outlines how the government will pursue them. Terms of reference, procedures and \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  guidelines for these programs have been clearly expressed in numerous executive rulings. \par \par \uc2  However, every time the government moves to sell particular assets or privatize particular state companies, it often becomes bogged down in endless debates in the House, resulting in governmental gridlock and, perhaps even more damage is done because it causes widespread \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about government \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Even more astonishing is the seemingly narrow-minded, nationalistic sentiments among House members even though they should be fully aware that foreign investors are virtually the only potential buyers of all the distressed assets. Our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is now like a profusely bleeding patient, which desperately requires a blood transfusion, and the only donors that are fit to provide the blood are businesspeople and investors from other countries. \par \par \uc2  House members may not be aware that the quality of distressed assets is now deteriorating rapidly due to a lack of lifeblood (working capital credits) and, that many assets, such as banks, are kept alive only by funds from the taxpayers (state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  support). \par \par \uc2  The House need not worry that foreign acquisition of some assets or state companies would give overseas investors a blank check to do whatever they like in our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . We have laws and regulations to ensure sound business practices and direct businesses into the goals of our national development. \par \par \uc2  After all, we should not forget that it was our corrupt, collusive national conglomerates, and not foreign companies, that were partly responsible for our current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  troubles. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011003dxa40005n\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
