\par\par \b \uc2  TUESDAY'S EDITORIALS IN MAJOR INDONESIAN DAILIES. \b0\par\par\uc2 714 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 October 2001\par \uc2 ANTARA - The Indonesian National News Agency\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Asia Pulse Pte Limited. Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its negligence or otherwise.\par \par \uc2  BETTER LATE THAN NEVER Better late than never? In the context of the current Indonesian situation there is reason to believe that the long delay in the government's readiness to consult leaders of the country's political, religious and social communities has not at this stage done irreparable harm to the country's stability. Responding to growing \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  clamor for the government to initiate open and candid discussions concerning the mounting \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  condemnation of the combined American-British assault in Afghanistan, the government invited leaders of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  last Friday to the State Palace for talks. Throughout the crisis here at home resulting from the September 11 attacks in the U.S and the ensuing British-American air and missile assault in Afghanistan, the government has been extremely slow to react. It is also obviously lacking in good \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  relations. \par \par \uc2   It is also difficult to deny, however, that President Megawati's silence on the matter is creating an impression of indecisiveness, or vacillating on her part in taking necessary decisions. This, of course, is unfortunate. One thing all Indonesians should heed at this moment of crisis is to put the nation's broader interest above everything else. Also, some serious soul-searching may be in order so Indonesians can see things in their proper perspective and act with insight and wisdom. - The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2  INVESTORS NEED LEGAL CERTAINTY The current Indonesia's investment condition is unfavourable, as it dropped by 78 percent in the January-September period. The drop, according to an official of the Coordinating Board of Investment, was due to the legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . It makes a sense, especially when the legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  is linked to security matters. Indonesia's investment in fact declined every year since the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis hit the country in mid 1997. The unfavourable climate has worsened due to mounting demonstrations against the U.S-British strikes on Afghanistan. If this instability persists, Indonesia's country risk may raise and foreign investors will likely be reluctant to put their capital in the country. Another hindrance for investment is the lack of upholding the law supremacy while the majority of the Indonesian people are expecting the government's seriousness in handling corruption, collusion and nepotism. It is time for the government to be consistent with its reform agenda. Among efforts is to take stern measures against those who disturb \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 's order. It was President Megawati herself who said that "no group nor country could make its own rules to commit violent acts against others." It was the President herself who was committed to eradicating corruption starting from her own circle. This commitment would be a good start in a process toward a credible and accountable state. - Bisnis Indonesia \par \par \uc2  WAITING FOR PRESIDENT MEGAWATI'S INITIATIVE The number of civilian casualties tends to increase, while the US seems to have no intention to stop its military offensive on Afghanistan. The former has instead showed its arrogance and obstinacy by closing all ways to compromise. This war is in fact no guarantee for the US to catch Osama bin Laden, live or dead. Others even say that the US will only repeat its folly in the Vietnam War. It is therefore comfortable, if the US will prefer a peaceful way. A diplomatic way. Halting a war will open the door of diplomacy. But the question is whether the US will listen to any call made by other countries or international institutions. People seem to be not confident of the United Nations' capability to serve as a mediator. And they could not also believe the US' allies and the Middle East which do not recognise the Taliban government. Then, whom will the people believe ? One of the answers is Indonesia. Indonesia should be able to mediate between the US and Afghanistan as this archipelagic country is the biggest moslem nation in the world. We want to say to the Megawati-led administration that Indonesia is important to the US, as important as the US to Indonesia. Thus, Ibu Mega, please say to President George W. Bush that war would not settle problems. It would even create new complication. And please say that Indonesia is ready to take initiative to hold discussions. - Media Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020011018dxag0005n\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
