\par\par \b \uc2  WEDNESDAY'S EDITORIALS IN INDONESIA'S MAJOR DAILIES. \b0\par\par\uc2 826 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 October 2001\par \uc2 ANTARA - The Indonesian National News Agency\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Asia Pulse Pte Limited. Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its negligence or otherwise.\par \par \uc2  MISGUIDED PRIORITIES It is, we feel, a totally misguided priority for President Megawati Soekarnoputri to leave the capital four days before Sunday's summit of the leaders of the Asia Pacific \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation forum in Shanghai. However important her presence may be in Shanghai to introduce herself to other APEC leaders, the President's departure could be postponed until Friday to provide her with more time to manage the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, which has now become much more complicated following the wave of anti-American demonstrations. Megawati and the government in general should realize that the continuing tide of anti-American demonstrations, though representing no more than the actions of an emotionally-charged minority, have created a new kind of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  regarding Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook. \par \par \uc2   It is therefore high time for Megawati and her government to really start leading and governing the nation by focusing their attention on managing the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis that has forced tens of millions of people into unemployment and absolute poverty, and deprived millions of children basic health services and primary education. - The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2  A DREAM TO FIGHT AGAINST THE US The way to fight against the United States is by boycotting all products of the superpower country. The spirit "to fight" against the superpower is an extraordinary courage. It is right that we start it with a dream. A dream to "defeat" the big and strong party. But there is no single nation which can live in a dream forever. A dream is needed to start achieving ideals. It is thus not enough to merely make rhetoric or burn flags to defeat the United States. We should be smart. So, starting from now we have to study harder and formulating a good education system which will produce skilled and clever people. We have to be honest and transparent as well better that the American people are. We have to work harder! Do not enter the politics for money. Respect the law and do not behave like Rambo. Above all, we have to stay united. Do not think that you are the only right people. Respect other people and exercise tolerance. We have no choice. A nation cannot "defeat" other nations by only having a dream. - Media Indonesia \par \par \uc2  PRESSURES SHOULD CONTINUE President Megawati Soekarnoputri has fulfilled demands conveyed by various parties that the government must show strong attitude over the US-led strikes on Afghanistan. Although she did not directly mention the US, anyone listening to her speech made on last Sunday evening on the occasion of Isra Mi'raj (Islamic day to commemorate Prophet Muhammad's miraculous flight from Mecca to Jerusalem) will easily understand that her call on any nation not to strike others was addressed to those which bombarded the poor Islamic country of Afghanistan. It means that the government, the \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and demonstrators have achieved the same understanding that they have to give high pressure on the US so as to make the superpower stop its military actions. This stance should be maintained until the United States pulls out its war machines and carries out more civilized ways. So, please continue to protest because the US deserves the protests to stop exercising arrogance. - Republika \par \par \uc2  BETWEEN APEC AND TERRORISM As U.S. bombardments of Afghanistan continue, 21 APEC member countries today open a meeting in Shanghai which local officials have been touting as "the most secure city in the world". The APEC meeting is scheduled to be capped off with a summit of the leaders of member countries on October 21. One of the country leaders to attend the APEC meeting in Shanghai is Indonesian President Megawati Soekarnoputri. So far, APEC member countries have shown varying attitudes toward the U.S. military strikes against Afghanistan. Some of them support the U.S. action, others have voiced conditional support, and still others have expressed opposition. What about Indonesia? Responding to growing domestic pressure to show a tougher stand, President Megawati issued a veiled condemnation of the U.S. attacks. She said terrorists should be punished, but it was wrong to try to capture them by attacking another country as such action would be against the law. Every action to fight terrorism should be taken with due respect for existing laws. Otherwise, "the actions designed to combat violence and terrorism will themselves amount to violence and terror," she said without mentioning the U.S. Washington may not like, or even be mad about, the Indonesian government's attitude as expressed by President Megawati. But this is the risk that must be accepted by Indonesia whose Muslim citizens have often been disappointed by the attitudes of the West which often puts the label of "terrorist" on Islam. At the APEC forum, Indonesia should reiterate that the fight against terrorism will be more effective if efforts are made first to establish what it is that leads to acts of terror being committed. - Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020011019dxah00004\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
