\par\par \b \uc2  Misguided priorities. \b0\par\par\uc2 641 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 October 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  It is, we feel, a totally misguided priority for President Megawati Soekarnoputri to leave the capital four days before Sunday's summit of the leaders of the Asia Pacific \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation forum in Shanghai. \par \par \uc2  However important her presence may be in Shanghai to introduce herself to other APEC leaders, the President's departure could be postponed until Friday to provide her with more time to manage the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, which has now become much more complicated following the wave of anti-American demonstrations. \par \par \uc2  By leaving on Wednesday and \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  two nights in Hong Kong, Megawati demonstrates not only her virtual ignorance of the real magnitude of the crisis she is facing, but also a complete lack of awareness that an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis needs emergency treatment and daily monitoring. \par \par \uc2  After all, the coming APEC summit will be heavily political in nature, thereby rather irrelevant with regard to Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  woes, and likely be dominated by the U.S. agenda to build up a stronger global alliance against terrorism. \par \par \uc2  Megawati and the government in general should realize that the continuing tide of anti-American demonstrations, though representing no more than the actions of an emotionally-charged minority, have created a new kind of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  regarding Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook. \par \par \uc2  Businesspeople are worried about the danger of an Islamic backlash at home due to the U.S.-led international fight against alleged terrorist bastions in Afghanistan and how it will affect Megawati's administration. They are nervous and apprehensive that the anti-American sentiment, if not well-managed, could escalate into the rising prominence of anti-foreign interests in the country. \par \par \uc2  Even without the new \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the weak \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was already hit severely by the far-reaching impacts of the September 11 terrorist attacks. Some exporters, faced with dwindling import orders from the U.S., have begun laying off employees. \par \par \uc2  This \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  is certainly inimical to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity, as businesspeople, faced with incalculable risks, are forced to postpone decisions. Consumers with large sums of disposable income may also be prompted to postpone purchases, preferring to keep their savings in short-term rupiah or dollar deposits. \par \par \uc2  This extreme lack of business and consumer confidence can be seen in the wildly-fluctuating rupiah rate against the American dollar and the persistently depressed condition of the Jakarta stock exchange. \par \par \uc2  The perceived condition of insecurity and the weaker \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  are especially damaging to the restructuring process of the banking industry, which could drag more businesses into trouble. This, in turn, would worsen the financial distress of banks at a time when many of them are still struggling to achieve the mandated minimum capital adequacy ratio of 8 percent by December. \par \par \uc2  The perceived high risks within the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  are also discouraging banks from expanding lending operations to the liquidity-starved business sector because of the big dangers of suffering new bad loans. This adverse condition could put more banks in danger of failure, with more devastating repercussions on the government because almost 90 percent of the banking industry has been nationalized. \par \par \uc2  The new \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  is also hindering the process of corporate debt restructuring, a prerequisite to a sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, as debtors have to come up with credible business plans to support their debt-restructuring schemes. But how could one produce a reliable business plan faced with this \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 ? \par \par \uc2  Likewise, asset recovery by the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA) is also being frustrated by the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  as investors are jittery about acquiring assets in a country perceived to be high risk. \par \par \uc2  It is therefore high time for Megawati and her government to really start leading and governing the nation by focusing their attention on managing the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis that has forced tens of millions of people into unemployment and absolute poverty, and deprived millions of children basic health services and primary education. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011016dxah000b8\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
