\par\par \b \uc2  Leadership urgent to rescue  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\uc2 . \b0\par\par\uc2 1,008 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 October 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  3 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Hadi Soesastro, Economist, Centre for Strategic International Studies, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the recovery of which has been weak and fragile, is being threatened by external and internal developments. The world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is rapidly slowing down with the possibility of entering into recession. The U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which has been an important locomotive for the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , began to show a slowing down at the beginning of this year. \par \par \uc2  Some believed that this would happen earlier because it could not continue to expand at a rate of growth that was near full employment for as long as it did. The third quarter of this year saw negative growth. \par \par \uc2  The Sept. 11 terrorist attacks on the heart of the U.S. financial center may send the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  into a recession, that is, experiencing negative growth in, at least, two quarters in a row. Early prediction suggests that by the second semester of 2002 the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  could take off again. The recession in the U.S. may not be deep as the government will pour liquidity into the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , in part to finance the "war" against international terrorism. \par \par \uc2  Can the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  wait for the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to pull up the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  again? Under the most favorable conditions this would mean that we would have to wait a whole year before the external environment again became favorable. East Asian economies would be severely affected by this downturn. They were helped greatly in 1999 and 2000 in overcoming the crisis by the strong growth of the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  led by the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Thailand and Korea were able to come out of the crisis because of this favorable external environment. Now, they and others will be negatively affected by this development. Even Singapore is currently experiencing negative growth of more than 5 percent. Many other regional economies that depend heavily on exports to the U.S. market, including Malaysia, are already feeling the pinch. Indonesian exports will definitely be hit, even though perhaps not as hard as its neighbors. \par \par \uc2  Various exporters, in particular of labor-intensive manufactured products, have stated that their exports will drop by between 20 percent and 40 percent. In fact, a major portion of this decline may be accounted for by either the cancellation of orders or as a consequence of a relocation of production, in large extent due to increased domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  These internal factors have added severely to the effects of the global slowdown. The concern is that when the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovers these internal disturbances will remain. Investors, the markets and the informed \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  have thus far failed to see clear, coherent and firm policies on the part of the government to deal with these problems. \par \par \uc2  These domestic problems are reflected in the high-risk premium, which currently reaches somewhere in the order of 13 percent to 15 percent. With such a high risk premium there is no way the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  can lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  without resulting in destabilizing outflows of money and capital and a further weakening of the rupiah. \par \par \uc2  It is therefore very clear that to rescue the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would require, in the first instance, concerted and serious efforts to reduce the country's risk premium. In fact, these efforts are a prerequisite to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. The weak and fragile recovery of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is caused by the continued high risk premium. \par \par \uc2  To reduce this means, among other things, that the country's security and political stability must be steadily improved. They cannot be changed overnight, but visible progress is all that investors, the markets and the informed \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  expect. Equally important is steady improvements in the rule of law and the legal system. Another critical factor is the handling of labor problems. This in itself is a tall order, but a serious beginning in resolving those problems has to be made. \par \par \uc2  Our rescue agenda is not different from the agenda for recovery. In fact, the rescue agenda is substantially an acceleration of efforts to tackle the most important items in the recovery agenda. No new recipe is required. There is no need to look for radical, alternative measures. There are no quick fixes. \par \par \uc2  A breakthrough will be obtained only through hard work and determination to accelerate and strengthen the implementation of our recovery agenda. These require in the first instance political will and leadership. This will then have to be translated in decision-making mechanisms, such as in relation to corporate and debt restructuring. In this area, decisions have been extremely slow and bad. \par \par \uc2  In the very short term, asset disposal and privatization of some state enterprises that are already in the pipeline should be executed without further delay. The government needs successful cases quickly before the little confidence that is still left is totally lost. Without these measures, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  cannot be stimulated. \par \par \uc2  To be sure, reducing \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  may help the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and save the banking system from a possible collapse, but it will not stimulate investment. The \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is already in a critical stage. It cannot be expected to fuel the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by means of a \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  expansion. \par \par \uc2  In the view of the business community, rescuing the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  means both stimulating the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  through \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary means as well as to protect domestic industries from external competition. Protectionist pressures are on the rise. If the government fails to undertake the essential rescue efforts, namely to accelerate the implementation of the recovery agenda, the country and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will fall into an even deeper pit. \par \par \uc2  The end result would be a greater incidence of poverty and increased unemployment and a spiraling down of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  into a state of misery. It is a big puzzle as to why some groups in society care less about this real problem affecting a large portion of the population than religious solidarity. It would be an even a bigger puzzle if the government allowed itself to be captured by such misguided interest and aspirations. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011017dxah00004\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Trading of financial shares quiet. \b0\par\par\uc2 247 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 October 2001\par \