\par\par \b \uc2  Privatization needs  \highlight22\uc2 public \highlight\uc2  campaign, IMF says. \b0\par\par\uc2 446 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 October 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  20 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Berni K. Moestafa, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The International Monetary Fund (IMF) said a \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  awareness campaign promoting the importance of selling state assets was crucial to speeding up Indonesia's privatization process amid frequent opposition from various groups. \par \par \uc2  The IMF's senior representative for Jakarta, David C.L. Nellor, said on Tuesday that the government should communicate with the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the long-term benefits of privatization. \par \par \uc2  "The government must seek \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  support by explaining the benefit beyond the process (of privatization)," Nellor told a media briefing. \par \par \uc2  He acknowledged that privatization often becomes a sensitive issue, touching on concerns over ownership, and creates \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  for parties involved with the state firm. \par \par \uc2  "In any privatization, there are groups that tend to be harmed by this event," he said, citing as an example that England had faced opposition from trade unions when that country began privatizing state firms. \par \par \uc2  In Indonesia, opposition can range from trade unions, regional governments, to legislators concerned with foreign control. \par \par \uc2  The latest instance has been the planned divestment of cement firm PT Semen Gresik to the Mexican-based cement firm Cemex SA de CV. \par \par \uc2  Legislators argued the cement industry was too vital to be under foreign control. \par \par \uc2  Similar concerns were also aired in the planned sale of PT Bank Central Asia (BCA) and last year's sale of large palm plantation units to a Malaysian investor. \par \par \uc2  Such developments have resulted in the failure of the government to secure a single sale during the past nine months. \par \par \uc2  In the three months remaining until year's end, the government must rake in its entire 2001 revenue target of Rp 6.5 trillion (about US$640 million). \par \par \uc2  "There is some light at the end of this difficult process," Nellor added. \par \par \uc2  He said privatization promotes \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth through the inflow of investment. Proceeds from state asset sales could also be used to reduce the government's debt burden. \par \par \uc2  He said countries like Argentina, Mexico and Egypt had successfully lowered their debt to gross domestic product (GDP) ratios with the help of privatization. \par \par \uc2  That works in two ways, as privatization raises GDP, while its proceeds lowers the debt burden, Nellor explained. \par \par \uc2  He also said that privatized firms tend to become more efficient so that, in the long-run, they would earn the government higher \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue. \par \par \uc2  Separately, American business consultant James Castle suggested the government and legislators agree on a set of guidelines for privatization. This, he said, should avoid the problems the government faces now. \par \par \uc2  Economist Dradjad Wibowo has warned that legislators meddling with asset sales could become a new source of risk to foreign investors. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011024dxao00060\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
