\par\par \b \uc2  Megawati paints grim  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  picture. \b0\par\par\uc2 757 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 November 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Fabiola Desy Unidjaja, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  President Megawati Soekarnoputri admitted on Thursday that she had done little to bring Indonesia out of its prolonged \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, and offered no fresh initiatives to address the political and social woes beleaguering the country, and scaring off investment. \par \par \uc2  "It is with serious concern and humility, but also frankness, that I have to admit that there is little good news that I can report to you," Megawati said in her first progress report to the members of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), the country's highest \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  body. \par \par \uc2  Megawati, who assumed the presidency on July 23 after MPR members impeached erratic former president Abdurrahman Wahid, warned that the country's debts had reached an alarming level, and that most of the State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  funds were used up on debt repayments and interest. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia's offshore debts now stood at around US$140 billion, of which 54 percent were government debts. \par \par \uc2  Fresh foreign investments had dried up over concerns that the country was a high-risk destination, she added. \par \par \uc2  "The data that we have shows that we have slid back to being a nation with a low per capita income, with the unemployment rate mounting, and with a very large part of production potential being unable to operate to the fullest," Megawati said. \par \par \uc2  She underlined the weakness of the country's banking sector, which had yet to recover fully after the financial crisis first broke in 1997, even though the government had spent a huge amount of money on recapitalizing domestic banks. \par \par \uc2  Megawati said efforts to privatize state-owned enterprises and sell assets currently managed by the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA), which were expected to cover the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , had not been going smoothly. \par \par \uc2  The government hoped to contain this year's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  at Rp 54.31 trillion, or 3.7 percent of gross domestic product (GDP). \par \par \uc2  To help cover the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the government has targeted privatization proceeds of Rp 6.5 trillion (about $633 million), plus Rp 27 trillion from the sale of assets under the stewardship of the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA). \par \par \uc2  The other source of financing for the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  is foreign loans. \par \par \uc2  There have been no proceeds from privatization so far, while as of September, IBRA was Rp 8 trillion behind target. \par \par \uc2  Efforts to privatize state-owned enterprises and sell IBRA-held assets, however, have met strong resistance from both lawmakers and the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  at large. \par \par \uc2  Megawati said that the government had now decided to concentrate on three priorities, namely \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, normalization of the political situation, and law enforcement. \par \par \uc2  In her first state-of-the-nation address on Aug. 16, Megawati singled out six programs for her cabinet, which included maintaining national unity, continuing reform, democratization, and reviving the country's ailing \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Rising anti-American sentiment following the U.S.-led strike against Afghanistan, has affected the country's tourism sector, which usually serves as one of the country's sources of income. \par \par \uc2  In the past weeks, the rupiah has fallen once again to below Rp 10,000 per U.S. dollar due to the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  security situation. \par \par \uc2  "We have to be honest in admitting these conditions and we have put all of our efforts into preventing a further \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  4downturn ... We need the courage to make some daring decisions to get out of the crisis," she said. \par \par \uc2  "We have to improve our country's image so it will not be considered as one of the most risky countries for investment. By this means, maybe we could get investors interested in coming to the country," Megawati added. \par \par \uc2  The government should focus on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery as the first step to resolving other crises, and in this regard the government may have to take unpopular measures to improve the security situation in the country. \par \par \uc2  "Achieving \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery will have implications and consequences, and the first consequence is to impose strict efficiency at all levels and in all fields ... we have to cut our routine \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  so we can have more funds for productive fields," she said. \par \par \uc2  The government would also be forced gradually to raise the prices of a number of goods and services, such as fuel and electricity, and to take "other bitter steps", including in the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  field. She gave no details. \par \par \uc2  "The government has to take more resolute action to deal with the many problems that could endanger political stability and the greater interests of the people," Megawati remarked. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011102dxb20000r\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
