\par\par \b \uc2  W. Sumatra denies seizure of cement firm. \b0\par\par\uc2 692 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 November 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Adianto P. Simamora and Berni K. Moestafa, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Signaling that it was backing down from its controversial plan, the West Sumatra administration said on Monday that it had no intention of unilaterally taking over local cement-maker PT Semen Padang. \par \par \uc2  "There has been no expropriation of Semen Padang, the takeover statement is untrue," West Sumatra Governor Zainal Bakar told reporters after meeting with Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Dorodjatun Kuntjoro-Jakti and State Minister for State Enterprises Laksamana Sukardi at the finance ministry office. \par \par \uc2  Separately, the World Bank urged the government on Monday to immediately resolve the Semen Padang case, warning that the unilateral move by the West Sumatra administration could tempt other regions to take similar action with state companies. \par \par \uc2  "It's important that the government resolve this issue quickly," World Bank senior economist Vikram Nehru told reporters, pointing out that the central government must overrule the move by the provincial administration. \par \par \uc2  "Clearly, if this decision is allowed to stand then it will be a big blow to the privatization program of the government. \par \par \uc2  "It will lead to tremendous investor wariness and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the future possibilities of privatization," he said. \par \par \uc2  The West Sumatra administration declared last week that it had taken over the local unit of state-owned cement maker PT Semen Gresik to protest the government's plan to sell a majority stake in the state firm to Mexico-based cement giant Cemex SA de CV. \par \par \uc2  The move was approved by the provincial council, saying that starting from Nov. 1, Semen Padang was temporarily under the control of the people of West Sumatra and had been transferred to the West Sumatra government. \par \par \uc2  The illegal takeover was strongly criticized, as it could have further damaged the country's reputation in the international business community and hampered the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery process. \par \par \uc2  Analysts have said that the move was purely intended to protect the interests of certain members of the local political elite in retaining Semen Padang as their main cash cow. \par \par \uc2  Zainal declined to say much about the outcome of his meeting with the top \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ministers. \par \par \uc2  He said that the government had formed a special team to resolve the issue, and that the final decision was now in the hands of Dorodjatun. \par \par \uc2  But Zainal insisted that the West Sumatra demand for Semen Padang to be spun off from Semen Gresik remained. \par \par \uc2  Separately, the South Sulawesi government reiterated on Monday that it would not take over the operations of PT Semen Tonasa, another unit of Semen Gresik operating in the province. \par \par \uc2  "We will not follow West Sumatra's move, but we are firm in our demand to spin off Tonasa from Gresik," Syamsul Alambulu, a senior official in the South Sulawesi capital of Makasar and head of the spin-off team said, as quoted by Reuters. \par \par \uc2  However, he warned that an ultimatum was being prepared, giving the central government six months to spin off Tonasa. \par \par \uc2  "If the government fails, steps will be taken," Alambulu said. "But not in the form of taking over Tonasa unilaterally, because we understand how difficult it is for the government to settle this problem. \par \par \uc2  The local protest has hampered the government's effort to sell a 51 percent stake in Semen Gresik to Cemex via a put option (shareholder's contractual right to sell) that had to be extended from the initial Oct. 26 deadline to Dec. 14. \par \par \uc2  Cemex, the world's third-largest cement maker, already owns 25 percent of Semen Gresik. \par \par \uc2  The government had initially hoped to raise around $520 million from the Semen Gresik sale, which is some 80 percent of the government's 2001 privatization proceeds targets of Rp 6.5 trillion (about $634 million). \par \par \uc2  No proceeds have been collected from privatization as yet. \par \par \uc2  Elsewhere, Nehru would not speculate on whether the takeover moves would affect the outcome of this week's Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI) donors' meeting. \par \par \uc2  The government is planning to request $3 billion to $4 billion in new loans to help finance the 2002 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  from the country's traditional donors. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011106dxb60000j\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
