\par\par \b \uc2  WEDNESDAYS EDITORIALS IN INDONESIAS MAJOR DAILIES. \b0\par\par\uc2 977 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 November 2001\par \uc2 ANTARA - The Indonesian National News Agency\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Asia Pulse Pte Limited. Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its negligence or otherwise.\par \par \uc2  WELCOME PREMIER ZHU \par \par \uc2  A very special guest is coming to town this Wednesday: Chinese Prime Minister Zhu Rongji, who is starting his four-day official visit. The visit, the first by a Chinese prime minister to Indonesia in 11 years, is very special in more than one respect. Indonesia would do well to take advantage of and explore the opportunities presented by this occasion. \par \par \uc2  Although the majority of its massive 1.2 billion population still lives in poverty, and although on paper at least it is still a communist state, China is well on its way to rapidly becoming one of the world's major \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  powers. \par \par \uc2  China is already absorbing more than two-thirds of all the foreign direct investment bound for Asia, coming, of course, at the expense of other countries in the region, including Indonesia. Many Indonesian investors had themselves got their feet in China's door long before the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  back home tumbled. \par \par \uc2  The visit by Prime Minister Zhu Rongji offers a great opportunity for both countries to put that relationship on a new footing. Going by the news from Beijing last week, the visit will place a particular emphasis on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  cooperation. Zhu Rongji reportedly will be making a new pledge of assistance to Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia, like the rest of Asia, is well positioned to become one of the main recipients of China's investment if it plays its cards right. Allowing the Bank of China to reopen its office in Jakarta, for example, would be a step in that direction. \par \par \uc2  Zhu Rongji is the brain and the chief architect behind China's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  success. The former Shang-hai mayor guided China's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  through good and bad times in the last 10 years, first as deputy prime minister and, since 1998, as prime minister. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia could not be more privileged in having a man of Zhu Rongji's international stature as a guest. On that note, we wish to welcome the Prime Minister to Indonesia, and hope that his time here will be spent productively, for the benefit of the people of both countries. \par \par \uc2  WE ARE LIVING IN YEARS OF DANGER \par \par \uc2  We have once heard of a film about dangerous times in this country. The film, "The Year of Living Dangerously" which starred Mel Gibson, tells us about \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  times in the 1960s. \par \par \uc2  That dangerous time has recurred. The present condition could even be worse than that in 1965. Why? This is because the present condition is very different. We are living at a time when technology and information are advancing at a very rapid pace and competition is increasingly becoming fiercer. \par \par \uc2  We cannot imagine what will become of us, if we fail to get out of the crisis and become the most fragile nation amid global advancement. Some say we will become a pariah. \par \par \uc2      Are all these likely to happen?  Judging by the present \par \par \uc2  condition, it is possible for the unexpected to occur. \par \par \uc2      The amount of the country's foreign debts is about the same as \par \par \uc2  that of its gross domestic product, while domestic debts are about half of that amount. Ironically, this does not change the people's attitude and way of thinking. \par \par \uc2  Corruption, which has destroyed the nation, is rampant and has not subsided at all. Officials implicated in a number of corruption cases have been given honorable positions instead of being tried. They do not even feel guilty. \par \par \uc2  We have become a nation which destroys its own interests. Efforts to get the nation out of the crisis by launching privatization and divestment programs have met challenge instead of support. \par \par \uc2  The Semen Padang (cement industry) case is one example. \par \par \uc2  It will sound awkward if any legislator does not understand what the present condition of the nation is. \par \par \uc2  We feel that it is necessary to make a national agreement on the system and direction of future \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development. We could no longer take an ambivalent and unclear attitude in which on the one hand, we are gearing up for a market \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but on the other hand we reject privatization. - Kompas \par \par \uc2  MINISTER YUSRIL'S RADICAL MOVE \par \par \uc2      A radical move is badly needed to fight corruption, collusion \par \par \uc2  and nepotism (KKN) which have gripped the country for tens of years. \par \par \uc2      Justice and Human Rights Minister Yusril Ihza Mahendra said last \par \par \uc2  Monday that he is committed to taking radical moves to eradicate \par \par \uc2  corruption, collusion and nepotism. \par \par \uc2      The government has thus finalized a bill on the forming of a \par \par \uc2  corruption eradication commission.  The proposed independent \par \par \uc2  commission will be tasked to investigate corruption cases. \par \par \uc2      We certainly fully support Minister Yusril's commitment because \par \par \uc2  he cannot make it happen alone. \par \par \uc2      Indonesia should be free from corruption, collusion and nepotism \par \par \uc2  because the people are already fed up with these bad practices. -Republika \par \par \uc2  A COMPROMISE OUTSIDE THE MPR MEETING \par \par \uc2  Two big political parties, the Indonesian Democratic Party-Struggle (PDIP) and Golkar Party, have finally come to an agreement on a crucial case - the second round of presidential elections and existence of the provincial \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  assembly. \par \par \uc2  What is wrong with the negotiation? What is worse about the lobby" Politics, like or not, is an art of possibility. One of them requires good skills in lobbying and negotiating, and that could be seen at the ongoing annual session of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR). \par \par \uc2  PDIP and Golkar could have a majority control in the MPR if they unite their votes. Compromise and fighting between them would affect the decisions of the MPR. That is the mathematics of gaining seats. \par \par \uc2  The problem is that the interest of each party is so huge in terms of maintaining its position in the 2004 general election. It is as expensive a bid for the future of the nation as changing the State Constitution through horse-trading. And for the short-term interest at that. - Media Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020011109dxb700001\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
