\par\par \b \uc2  Govt told to address domestic problems. \b0\par\par\uc2 684 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 November 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  3 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Muhammad Nafik, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The administration of President Megawati Soekarnoputri must resolve domestic problems such as security and legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in order to bring the country out of its current crisis, observers said on Friday. \par \par \uc2  "We should shift our attention from global problems to domestic issues," political observer Dewi Fortuna Anwar told a seminar on The Implications of International Terrorism and U.S. Attacks on Afghanistan against Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Politics in Jakarta. \par \par \uc2  "The government's failure to boost security and guarantee legal certainty has hindered the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery," she added. \par \par \uc2  Economist Umar Juoro of the Center for Information and Development Studies (CIDeS) and researcher Rizal Sukma of the Center of Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) concurred, saying domestic non-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  factors constituted the main obstacles to recovery. \par \par \uc2  "Focusing on domestic problems is an urgent issue to eliminate \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  among investors," Umar said. \par \par \uc2  He said the nation's unresolved major problems included the privatization program, banking restructuring, the sales of state assets under Indonesia's Bank Restructuring Agency and the rescheduling of private debts. \par \par \uc2  He cited the West Sumatra administration's much-criticized takeover of state-owned cement firm PT Semen Padang and unclear \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  on the sale of government shares in publicly-listed company Bank Central Asia (BCA). \par \par \uc2  Rizal said many crucial problems, such as continued unrest in the provinces such as Aceh and the Maluku islands had to be resolved immediately to restore peace across the country. \par \par \uc2  "Many deaths have taken place in Aceh and other regions, but Jakarta is still silent. Why should we give too much attention to Afghanistan, while we have a similar problem at home?" he asked. \par \par \uc2  Umar said global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recession was not an excuse for the government not to address the nation's complicated problems exacerbated by erratic policies and the Sept. 11 terrorist attacks in the U.S. \par \par \uc2  Although Indonesia depended on the U.S. and other industrialized countries, it should now count on domestic resources to survive and restore the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "We should create a safe climate at home free from terrorist threats or radical actions leading to violence that has damaged the trust of domestic and foreign businessmen," Umar said. \par \par \uc2  Apart from the terrorism, he added that the government should take a moderate measure to push for talks with Muslim leaders in efforts to help secure the national situation. \par \par \uc2  On Thursday, Muslim scholars urged the government and the country's two largest Islamic organizations - Nahdlatul Ulama and Muhammadiyah - to invite extremist leaders for talks to prevent possible terror attacks. \par \par \uc2  Both NU and Muhammadiyah have agreed to take the lead in countering militant groups in effort to restore the Indonesian image of Islam, which has been tarnished by their recent anti-U.S. protests. \par \par \uc2  Researcher Rizal Sukma of the CSIS told Thursday's seminar that the U.S. tragedy had "revealed the new face of international terrorism". \par \par \uc2  However, he said Indonesia should take into account the voices of Muslims at home and national interests in responding to the U.S.-led campaign against terrorism. \par \par \uc2  Rizal and Dewi lauded the government's stance in reaction to the international campaign against terror. Jakarta has condemned the Sept. 11 terrorist attacks and has at the same time asked the U.S. and its Western allies to stop bombing Afghanistan. \par \par \uc2  Dewi dismissed worries over a possible withdrawal of U.S. support for Indonesia should it take a firm stance against U.S strikes in Afghanistan. \par \par \uc2  "America will continue backing us because it's also of its own interest to forge relations with moderate Muslim countries, like Indonesia," she said. \par \par \uc2  She added that as the world's largest Muslim nation, Indonesia should even strengthen its bargaining power in the international community following the U.S. tragedy blamed on Osama bin Laden and the Taliban. \par \par \uc2  Dewi also said it was impossible to heed the demand by a minority group of Muslims to cut diplomatic ties with the U.S. as the majority of the people has realized that relations with the superpower were important. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011109dxba0005q\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
