\par\par \b \uc2  ADB cuts RI growth forecast to 3.2%. \b0\par\par\uc2 552 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 November 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  20 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Moch. M. Kurniawan, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Indonesia's predicted \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth this year has been slashed by about 25 per cent, the Asian Development Bank (ADB) said on Friday. \par \par \uc2  ADB revised its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth forecast for Indonesia this year from the 4.2 percent predicted in April to just 3.2 percent due to a global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recession deepened by the Sept. 11 terrorist attacks on the U.S. \par \par \uc2  ADB also cut its 2002 growth forecast from 4.5 percent to 3.9 percent. \par \par \uc2  "Higher growth will be possible (next year) with significant improvements in political and security conditions," it said in its latest outlook report on Asia. \par \par \uc2  The government predicted the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would grow by 3.5 percent this year, and 4 percent next year. The initial government forecast for 2002 was 5 percent. Last year, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  grew by a hefty 4.8 percent mainly driven by strong export performances and rising oil prices. \par \par \uc2  Analysts have said that the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slump would negatively affect Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as exports fall. \par \par \uc2  The cut in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  forecast increases the threat of greater unemployment in the country of more than 200 million people already badly affected by years of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis and political upheaval. \par \par \uc2  On Thursday, Indonesia's key donors, under the umbrella of the Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI), pledged some US$3.14 billion in new loans to help finance the 2002 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  plus $586 million in grants and technical assistance. \par \par \uc2  The government is scheduled to meet the Paris Club of creditor nations in February next year to seek a rescheduling facility for some Rp 27 trillion (about $2.6 billion) in sovereign debt. \par \par \uc2  Elsewhere, ADB said inflation this year might hit 11 percent due to a weaker rupiah, accommodative monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and hikes in administered prices such as fuel and electricity. \par \par \uc2  For 2002, inflation would stay at 9 percent although it would go beyond an earlier prediction of 6 percent, the Bank said. \par \par \uc2  ADB said that despite renewed optimism following the election of President Megawati Soekarnoputri late in July, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was plagued with new \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  due to negative publicity resulting from rising anti-U.S. protest at home in the wake of the U.S.-led attacks on Afghanistan. \par \par \uc2  The Bank said this would likely further reduce potential investment inflows "and perhaps exacerbate capital flight from the country." \par \par \uc2  ADB said the government must pursue policies to stabilize the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and relaunch tough reforms that are needed to stimulate the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The Bank also warned that the government should speed up asset sales and privatization. \par \par \uc2  "Failure to meet the privatization and asset sales targets will jeopardize recovery prospects and further restrict development investment," ADB said. \par \par \uc2  On the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook for other countries in the region, ADB said that Singapore, Taiwan, South Korea, and Hong Kong, had seen their economies suffer serious setbacks due to the impact of the world slump. \par \par \uc2  These countries were expected to undergo an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  contraction in 2001, except for Korea which was forecast to eke out 2 percent growth after expanding by 8.8 percent in 2000. \par \par \uc2  China's forecast remains unchanged from ADB's April report at 7.3 percent this year, the region's highest growth forecast. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011109dxba00069\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
