\par\par \b \uc2  FRIDAY'S EDITORIALS OF INDONESIA'S MAJOR DAILIES. \b0\par\par\uc2 766 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 November 2001\par \uc2 ANTARA - The Indonesian National News Agency\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Asia Pulse Pte Limited. Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its negligence or otherwise.\par \par \uc2  REDUCING DEBT BURDENS \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian government often looks highly ingenious at simplifying complex problem in a bid to dismiss the great concerns about its distressed financial condition. Its latest idea was unveiled in Minister of Finance Boediono's statement last week that the government would issue treasury bills next year to gradually replace the Rp 674.4 trillion (US$ 64.2 billion) bonds that start maturing in 2002. \par \par \uc2  Earlier in September Boediono said asset sales, privatization and corporate debt restructuring would be accelerated next year to enable the government to retire early RP 25.8 trillion in bonds, thereby reducing the deadweight cost of the huge domestic debt overhang. \par \par \uc2  First of all, the revenue targets set for the sale of assets by the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency and privatization of state companies next year appear to be ambitious be cause a portion of the sale proceeds will be used to plug part of the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The new targets require a total revenue of Rp 43.7 trillion from the two programs next year, while during the current \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year only Rp 20.5 trillion of the Rp 33.5 trillion target had been achieved as of October. \par \par \uc2  Issuing T-bills discounted debt instruments of one year or less that pays its face value at maturity, is even more complex and greatly challenging, even though that instrument is badly needed now to help increase the depth of the financial market. Because, unlike the government bonds already in circulation, T-bills will perform double function of raising fund and setting benchmark \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Needless to say, the government should work harder to reduce the sovereign risk to facilitate the issuance of T-bills. The most effective way of decreasing the sovereign risks is to accelerate the pace of reform measures, including the cleaning up of the banking industry, asset sales, privatization and stronger law enforcement. Without significant progress in these areas, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook will remain bleak. Obviously, the market will not buy debt instruments from a government with distressed financial prospects. - The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2  A SHOW FROM THE OVAL BUILDING \par \par \uc2  The case of the non-budgetary funds of the State Logistics Agency (Bulog) has turned into a great show. After being questioned by the Attorney General's Office, witnesses have given contradicting statements. Obviously, this has become an added attraction to the show. The Attorney General's Office's oval building has become an amazing stage for the show. \par \par \uc2  The case itself is simple. It is all about Bulog's Rp 54.6 billion in non-budgetary funds, which had allegedly been embezzled. It is obviously a case of money stolen from the state. All the prosecutor has to do is to gather evidences and bring those involved in the action to court - whoever they are. Unfortunately, this has not occurred. The Attorney General's Office has a greater reputation for mounting shows on stage than in court. \par \par \uc2  The court however is no more than a place for make-up. The case of Bank Bali for instance, which had inflicted a loss of Rp 904.6 billion to the state, has failed to bring Joko Tjandra to jail. \par \par \uc2  Is Megawati's government also doing a play on stage or is it determined to eliminate corruption, collusion and nepotism? - Media Indonesia \par \par \uc2  WILL INCREASING ELECTRICITY RATES SOLVE THE COUNTRY'S PROBLEMS? \par \par \uc2  The government plans to raise electricity rates by 6 percent every three months starting January 2002. The plan is awaiting presidential approval. \par \par \uc2  Amid the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation in the country, not to mention problems on workers who had been laid off and low income, the government plan to increase electricity rates will only make the people suffer more. \par \par \uc2  The government is likely to raise oil prices, telephone rates \par \par \uc2  and toll road fees as well next year. \par \par \uc2  The toll road management company, PT Jasa Marga, has proposed a \par \par \uc2  toll increase of 30 percent in 2002; the state telecommunications company, PT Telkom, plans to raise telephone rates by 21.67 percent; and the state oil and gas company, Pertamina, plans to raise gasoline prices by 25.16 percent to 30.13 percent. \par \par \uc2  Considering the prolonged \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis in the country, the \par \par \uc2  people will certainly not be happy with these plans. \par \par \uc2  On the other hand, it would also be difficult for the government \par \par \uc2  if it does not reduce its \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  to the electricity and oil and \par \par \uc2  gas sectors. \par \par \uc2  Will the plan to increase such rates solve the country's \par \par \uc2  problems? If not, until when will the government implement this \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ? - Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020011128dxbn00003\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
