\par\par \b \uc2  Government plans Indonesian Recovery Fund. \b0\par\par\uc2 723 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 November 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Tantri Yuliandini and Kornelius Purba, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The government is planning to launch a joint fund with foreign institutions early next year to provide Indonesia with much needed investment to boost the corporate sector and to provide jobs for the people, according to Minister of Industry and Trade Rini Soewandi. \par \par \uc2  Rini said on Friday that the fund, to be called the Indonesian Recovery Fund, would be similar to the one in Thailand, which implemented the plan a year after it was hit by the 1997 regional financial crisis. \par \par \uc2  "We have proposed the setting up of the Indonesian Recovery Fund ... which will invest at home to help create more jobs," she told reporters following a Cabinet meeting, adding that the plan had been approved by the Cabinet. \par \par \uc2  Rini said that initial funding for the fund was expected to reach US$200 million in which the government may have to contribute $10 million. \par \par \uc2  She said that this would also be a type of trial to see how interested foreign investors were in putting their money back into Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  "We hope to be able to attract reputable institutions such as the IFC, so that it would draw other investors to put in their money," Rini said, referring to the International Finance Corporation, the investment arm of the World Bank. \par \par \uc2  The stakeholders would determine how the fund is managed and, taking into consideration the government's priorities, they would also determine which industries it would invest in. \par \par \uc2  "The government would act as advisor," Rini said. \par \par \uc2  But she said that details of the fund would still have to be discussed with the Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Dorodjatun Kuntjoro-Jakti and Finance Minister Boediono. \par \par \uc2  She explained that Thailand had invited foreign institutions such as the IFC, the Asian Development Bank (ADB), and Merryl Lynch, to put money in the joint fund, after which the fund used the money to invest in various corporations in the country. \par \par \uc2  "It (the fund) succeeded in Thailand, and it has withdrawn about US$1.6 billion (from it)," she said. \par \par \uc2  However, Rini did not explain why Indonesia waited for such a long time before setting up such a fund. \par \par \uc2  The recovery fund in Thailand was initiated in 1998 following the fourth annual meeting of the Thailand-U.S. Business Council. \par \par \uc2  Among of the investors in the Thailand fund are ADB, Japan Bank for International Cooperation (JBIC), Kreditanstalt fur Wiederaufbau (KfW) of Germany, and State Street Corporation of the United States. \par \par \uc2  The fund invests in companies which are expanding or restructuring and, to a limited extent, in start-up companies. \par \par \uc2  Since the Asian financial crisis, many small and medium-sized enterprises have limited access to financing for expansion or restructuring. The fund helped to address this problem and assisted in restoring investor confidence in the Thai \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Amid the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recession and depressed sentiment at home, Indonesia would need a significant boost in foreign investment to help meet the 2002 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth target of around 4 percent. \par \par \uc2  Foreign investors have largely shunned Indonesia since the country experienced a combination of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political woes in 1998. \par \par \uc2  During the first nine months of 2001, foreign direct investment dropped by more than 50 percent to $6.05 billion compared to the same period last year due to various \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Rini stressed the need for the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA) to quickly restructure the debts of some 350 exporting companies. \par \par \uc2  "The largest absorption of workers is from export-oriented companies ... many of these are still under IBRA," she said, adding that she hoped that after IBRA finalizes the restructuring of these companies they could work for expansion. \par \par \uc2  Export-oriented companies include those in textiles and garments, footwear, electronics, wood and wood products, also crude palm oil (CPO) and its derivatives. \par \par \uc2  Without debt restructuring, the companies would have difficulty obtaining credit lines to finance operations. \par \par \uc2  Rini said that \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Governor Syahril Sabirin, who also attended the Cabinet meeting, would study a credit scheme for the financing of capital goods such as machinery to replace outdated machinery. \par \par \uc2  "We hope the machinery will be supplied by local producers," she said. \par \par \uc2  Indonesian banks have been reluctant to resume lending activities due to a combination of weak capital and high risk associated with lending to local companies. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011126dxbo000bt\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  'IRF insufficient to resolve systemic problem'. \b0\par\par\uc2 342 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 November 2001\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Industrialists have hailed the plan to set up the Indonesia Recovery Fund (IRF), but have reminded the government to prioritize problems they described as 'systemic' such as legal certainty, security and labor. \par \par \uc2  Senior executive of the Indonesian chamber of commerce and industry (Kadin Indonesia), Anton J. Supit, told Bisnis that those issues are more serious than funds. \par \par \uc2  Anton added that another issue is lack of coordination among ministries that hamper the real sector. \par \par \uc2  "The business world is still waiting for the government to take concrete measures on laws, security and labor. It prevents investors from coming in," he said. \par \par \uc2  He noted that exports drop because buyers are not sure about domestic security, and that most of them have shifted to other countries. \par \par \uc2  Textile businessman Natsir Mansyur agreed, saying that the IRF is a concrete step to deal with complex problems in the real sector. \par \par \uc2  "The IRF deals with financial matters, but not such issues as laws, security and labor," said Natsir. \par \par \uc2  He said the textile and garment (TPT) industry needs to be revitalized as 120 companies are now being restructured by IBRA because of their debts. \par \par \uc2  Electronic goods businessman Lee Kang Hyun said the IRF is "quite ideal", but he questioned its benefit to the electronics industry. \par \par \uc2  He said global investors dominate the electronic goods industry and that any problem related to that is dealt with by principals. \par \par \uc2  "The main issue is \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in politics, security and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and government policies in \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  matters," he said. \par \par \uc2  He said few electronic firms have debt problems and that their contribution to exports is relatively small. \par \par \uc2  Lee said that total exports of electronic goods stand at US$7 billion last year, US$4 billion of which came from Matsushita, Samsung, Epson, LG, Toshiba, Sanyo, Sony and Aiwa. \par \par \uc2  Palm oil businessman Derom Bangun, meanwhile, also praised the IRF but sought more detail in terms of its implementation. \par \par \uc2  Derom noted that banks have begun 