\par\par \b  \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal \highlight\uc2  distress following the 1997-1998 crisis. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Anwar Nasution, Senior Deputy Governor, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Jakarta \par \uc2 1,098 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 December 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Part 2 of 2 \par \par \uc2  Over 55 percent of the external debt as of December 1998 (US$83.6 billion) is owed by the private sector and over 80 percent of it was received by the non-bank corporate entities. The average maturity of this external debt is approximately 1.5 years (J.P. Morgan, Global Data Watch, Jan. 16 1998). A significant portion of the private sector's external debts become contingency liability of the government as they are explicitly and implicitly guaranteed by the government. \par \par \uc2  Sovereign guarantees not only covered the external debt of the state-owned banks and non-bank companies. The guarantee also covered foreign liabilities of the private sector, particularly the politically well-connected private infrastructure providers. Afraid of severe damage to international transactions, the authorities, in 1998, introduced exchange offer scheme and extended coverage of the blanket guarantee scheme to include external liabilities of financially distressed domestic banks. \par \par \uc2  It is true that the bulk of the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector external debt is long-term in nature. This is because Indonesia's debt strategy since the late 1960s has been consistently to maximize the inflow of development aid from its Western and Japanese creditors. The "oil boom" enjoyed in the 1970s did not change this strategy: Together with the resulting rise in real income, it only shifted Indonesia's position to a less concessional aid package. \par \par \uc2  The associated principal and interest servicing cost of Indonesia's external debt, however, still runs high, at some $9 billion a year. To be able to repay its external debt, the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector has to accumulate a \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  surplus as well as a surplus in the balance of payments. To ease the pressures on the \b \highlight22\uc2 public budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the balance of payments, on Sept. 23, 1998, the Paris Club creditor nations agreed to reschedule $4.2 billion in principal repayments of Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  external debt. \par \par \uc2  Three institutions have been established to work out private sector external debt, namely: the Frankfurt Agreement, Indonesian Debt Restructuring Agency (INDRA) and the Jakarta Initiative. The private sector external debt is, however, relatively more difficult to settle as there is a big number of both foreign lenders and domestic borrowers. Each individual debtor has distinct willingness and ability to pay which different from one to another. Foreign lenders include foreign private banks, institutional investors and other non-bank entities. The progress of external debt work out, however, is very slow partly because of weak and inefficient legal and judicial system, particularly commercial court system and bankruptcy law. \par \par \uc2  In June 1998, the Frankfurt Agreement was signed by the government with international private bankers to restructure and maintain trade credit at the April 1998 level for one year. The trade credit was fully guaranteed by the government (administered by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) and had been extended for another year to April 2001. The non-bank corporate debt is rescheduled and restructured along the line of Mexican program. \par \par \uc2  A trust institution, called INDRA, was established under the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This institution provides exchange rate risk protection and assurance to the availability of foreign exchange to private debtors that agree with their foreign creditors to restructure their external debts for a period of eight years with three years of grace during which no principal will be payable. By the end of 1998, the program only attracted one debtor with a total debt value of $2.9 billion. As a result, the authorities have decided to close INDRA. \par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Initiative Task Force (JITF) is the third institution to deal with private sector external debt. Modeled after the London Initiative JITF is a private agency, financially supported by the government, to facilitate resolutions of debts among international creditors and domestic debtors outside the court system. By October 2001, term sheets had been signed for 60 cases totaling $12.4 billion in debt and nearly 50 percent of the cases have entered the stage of formal documentation and implementation. \par \par \uc2  The burden of debt service obligations will likely remain high in the years to come, particularly if \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth remains low. This and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  developments in international oil price requires more efforts to generate revenues from non-oil sources both through raising \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and selling of state assets. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  efforts to raise revenues include measures to improve custom and \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  administration and to remove VAT exemptions and reduce \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives. The \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  ratio (1999: 12 percent of gross domestic product) and number of individual \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  payers (2000: Less than 1 percent of total population) need to be increased. \par \par \uc2  To finance the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , we should continue to maximize the inflow of development aid from Western and Japanese creditors. Indonesia should also continue to negotiate for easing the burden of debt services. In addition, market for the huge amount of government bonds needs to be created, its infrastructure needs to be upgraded, institutional investors (such as pension funds and insurance companies) need to be created and strengthened. In addition, it should be made open to foreign investors in order to avoid overcrowding in the narrow and shallow domestic bond market. \par \par \uc2  Generating revenues from the sale of government assets is another option for financing government \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Privatization of state-owned enterprises (SOEs) is also part of the process to scale back the government's role in providing the private goods and services. The other source of government revenue is from the sale of assets now controlled by the Indonesia Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA). With the injection of government bonds, nearly all of domestic banks were nationalized. \par \par \uc2  IBRA's assets include non-performing loans, non-loan assets and majority equity stakes in 11 recapitalized banks. Privatization of SOEs and returning back IBRA's assets to private sector also serve as an instrument to improve the efficiency and productivity of productive assets and to speed up recovery. \par \par \uc2  The nascent democracy has strained relations between the executive and \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  branches and has contributed to disharmony between central and local governments, along with increased labor disputes. The investment climate has deteriorated further as social fabrics have begun to be affected by the ethnic, religious and separatist violence. \par \par \uc2  Since the past two years, 16 (out of some 190) non-bank state-owned enterprises have been announced for sale. Yet in reality, no transaction has been concluded in the past two years. \par \par \uc2  The above article is an excerpt of the writer's presentation at the 14th Pacific \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation Council in Hong Kong, on Nov. 28 - 30. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011214dxce0005m\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  'Pursuit of assets impedes recovery'. \b0\par\par\uc2 405 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 December 2001\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery is being impeded by the presence of 'old figures' in the government and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  institutions as well as the battle for assets controlled by the state, said economist Sri Adiningsih. \par \par \uc2  Problems surrounding privatization and divestment of government shares reflect the fierce battle between businessmen, politicians and investors, she added. \par \par \uc2  She noted that recent times have seen resistance against privatization of state firms coming not only from corporate boards, but also politician and local communities. \par \par \uc2  Sri told Bisnis that professionalism has taken a back seat as short-term interest dictates their stance on national assets. \par \par \uc2  She made the comments in reference to the new letter of intent with the IMF, which covers \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  strategies on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  The new LoI looks into efforts to stabilize the macro-\b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as well as the privatization and recovery of state firms (BPPN) assets and legal and governance reforms. \par \par \uc2  Sri said the situation is fraught with \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , leading many to capitalize for short-term gains. \par \par \uc2  "Those who are appointed officials do not know how long they will remain in their positions. Anything can change if the political situation changes," she said. \par \par \uc2  "There is no long-term vision. I'm worried that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would worsen." \par \par \uc2  Sri predicted that the battle would intensify next year, as interest groups, including political parties, need funds for the 2004 election. \par \par \uc2  She also sees \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conflicts rising in the regions and that it would reprised on the national level. \par \par \uc2  "There is no vision, morality and integrity among those in power, autonomy could come under threat," she said. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, economist Vincent Didiek Aryanto said the government must be able to achieve a \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  surplus of at least 2% of the GDP so that it would be able to manage foreign debts without burdening the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  APBN. \par \par \uc2  Vincent yesterday also said that foreign debt could be a time bomb and as such must be managed well. \par \par \uc2  He noted that Indonesia's foreign debt stands at US$146 billion, of which the government's portion is US$77 billion. \par \par \uc2  Of the total debt, he added, US$33.3 billion would mature this year, comprising US$7.3 billion government debt, US$23.1 billion private sector debt, US$1.8 billion in securities and US$1.1 billion in BUMN debts. \par \par \uc2  The situation exacerbates the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , as the DSR (debt service ratio) stands at 41%, up from 34%. (ts/bar). \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020011217dxcf00001\par }\par \b \uc2 Search Summary\b0\par \par  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx2000\clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx9072\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Text\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\a